  id: '91',
  title: 'Carbon Capture Technology',
  text: `As the limits of emissions reduction strategies become increasingly apparent, scientists and policymakers have turned growing attention to carbon capture and storage (CCS) technologies — methods for physically removing carbon dioxide from the atmosphere or at the point of industrial emission and storing it in geological formations, deep ocean environments, or solid mineral compounds. Proponents view CCS as an essential complement to renewable energy deployment, arguing that the scale and speed of decarbonisation required to meet the Paris Agreement temperature targets cannot be achieved through emissions reduction alone.

Two broad categories of CCS technology exist. The first involves capturing CO₂ directly at point sources — primarily fossil fuel power stations and industrial facilities such as cement and steel plants — before it enters the atmosphere. This approach is technically mature in some applications and has been deployed commercially, but it is expensive and only addresses emissions from large fixed sources rather than the broader economy. The second category, direct air capture (DAC), extracts CO₂ directly from ambient air using chemical processes, potentially enabling the removal of emissions from diffuse sources such as transport and agriculture. DAC is currently far more expensive than point-source capture and requires very large quantities of low-carbon energy to operate, limiting its near-term scalability.

Critics of CCS note that investment in carbon capture can create a moral hazard by providing fossil fuel industries with a technological rationale for continuing or expanding operations rather than transitioning to clean energy. They argue that CCS functions as a distraction from the more fundamental transformation of energy systems needed to address climate change. Supporters respond that given the carbon already emitted, some degree of removal will be necessary regardless of how rapidly emissions are cut, and that rejecting CCS on principle risks leaving the world without critical tools in a carbon-constrained future.`,
