  id: '93',
  title: 'Personalised Medicine',
  text: `Personalised medicine — also referred to as precision medicine — represents a paradigm shift in healthcare from a one-size-fits-all approach to treatment tailored to the individual characteristics of each patient. Central to this shift is the rapid development of genomic sequencing technologies, which can now map an individual's complete genetic code quickly and at rapidly declining cost. By identifying specific genetic variants associated with disease risk, drug metabolism, and treatment response, clinicians can in principle select therapies that are most likely to be effective for a particular patient while avoiding treatments likely to cause adverse effects.

Oncology has been at the forefront of personalised medicine, with targeted cancer therapies designed to attack tumour cells bearing specific genetic mutations rather than using broadly toxic chemotherapy regimens. The results in some cancers have been transformative: drugs targeting specific mutations in lung cancer, melanoma, and certain leukaemias have achieved response rates and survival outcomes previously unimaginable with conventional treatment. However, these successes coexist with significant limitations. Many targeted therapies eventually encounter resistance as tumour cells evolve new mutations; the genetic landscape of tumours is often highly heterogeneous, meaning that even a single tumour may contain multiple distinct cell populations requiring different treatments; and not all cancer types have well-characterised actionable mutations.

Beyond oncology, personalised medicine holds promise for pharmacogenomics — the study of how genetic variation affects drug response across all therapeutic areas — reducing the current practice of prescribing based on population averages. Critics, however, raise concerns about equity: genomic databases remain heavily skewed towards individuals of European ancestry, meaning that precision medicine tools may perform less well for patients of other ethnic backgrounds. Ensuring that the benefits of genomic medicine are distributed equitably across populations remains one of the field's most pressing ethical challenges.`,
