  id: '96',
  title: 'Marine Protected Areas',
  text: `Marine protected areas (MPAs) are designated zones of ocean in which human activities — particularly commercial fishing, oil and gas extraction, and coastal development — are restricted or prohibited to allow marine ecosystems to recover and sustain their biological productivity. Covering approximately 8% of the world's oceans as of recent estimates, MPAs represent one of the primary tools in the international effort to reverse the alarming decline of ocean biodiversity.

The scientific evidence supporting the effectiveness of well-managed MPAs is substantial. Studies comparing fished and protected areas consistently find that no-take reserves — zones where all extractive activities are banned — support significantly higher biomass, greater species diversity, and larger individual organisms than adjacent fished areas. The benefits of protection frequently extend beyond MPA boundaries through 'spillover', as fish populations recovering within protected zones spread into adjacent areas and replenish surrounding fisheries. This effect means that fishing communities operating near well-managed MPAs often report improved catches over the medium to long term, aligning conservation and livelihood objectives.

However, the effectiveness of MPAs depends critically on whether they are meaningfully enforced. Research has demonstrated a stark performance gap between 'paper parks' — MPAs that exist on maps but receive negligible management resources — and actively patrolled and managed reserves. In many low-income countries with extensive coastlines, the cost of effective marine patrol is prohibitive without international support. Illegal, unreported, and unregulated (IUU) fishing represents a persistent threat, with well-documented cases of fishing vessels operating inside designated protected areas with impunity.

Conservation organisations increasingly argue that the global target of protecting 30% of the ocean by 2030 — endorsed by the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework — is achievable but will require a fundamental increase in both the financing and governance capacity dedicated to MPA management, particularly in the developing world.`,
