  id: '98',
  title: 'The Role of Cities in Climate Action',
  text: `While much climate policy attention focuses on national governments and international agreements, cities have emerged as critical arenas for climate action, accounting for approximately 70% of global energy-related carbon emissions while covering less than 3% of the Earth's land surface. The concentration of people, economic activity, and infrastructure in urban areas makes cities simultaneously the largest contributors to the climate crisis and the most strategically important sites for emissions reduction.

Cities possess unique governance advantages in climate action. Unlike national governments, which must navigate complex geopolitical negotiations and politically contentious federal-level legislation, mayors and city councils often have direct jurisdiction over land use, building codes, public transport systems, and local energy procurement — the very domains where emissions reductions are most achievable. Several cities have demonstrated that ambitious climate targets are politically viable and economically productive: Copenhagen has developed a credible pathway to carbon neutrality, while cities including Oslo and Amsterdam have made substantial progress in phasing out fossil fuel vehicles from urban centres.

However, cities also face distinctive constraints. Many of the most ambitious interventions — such as retrofitting existing building stock for energy efficiency at scale — require sustained capital investment over decades, which is challenging for municipalities that typically operate on annual budget cycles and have limited capacity to absorb long-term debt. Cities in the developing world face additional challenges, as rapid urbanisation means that vast quantities of new infrastructure must be built, and there is an enormous risk that this infrastructure will lock in high-carbon patterns for generations if it is not deliberately designed and financed to be low-carbon from the outset.

International climate finance mechanisms have been criticised for being too slow, too complicated, and too focused on national governments to effectively reach the urban scale where much of the critical action must take place.`,
