  id: '108',
  title: 'The Anthropocene',
  text: `The Anthropocene is a proposed geological epoch defined by the dominant influence of human activity on Earth's geology and ecosystems. Although not yet formally ratified by the International Commission on Stratigraphy, the concept has gained enormous traction across scientific disciplines, reflecting growing recognition that humanity has become the primary driver of change in the Earth system — a development with few precedents in the 4.5-billion-year history of the planet.

The physical signatures of human impact are now detectable across the geological record in ways that future geologists would be able to identify. These include the global dispersal of synthetic materials including plastics, concrete, and aluminium alloys that were absent from the geological record before the twentieth century; a sharp spike in radioactive isotopes following mid-twentieth-century nuclear weapons testing; significant changes in the carbon and nitrogen isotope ratios of sediments; and what researchers are calling the sixth mass extinction event, with species disappearing at rates estimated to be between 100 and 1,000 times the background extinction rate that characterised most of Earth's history.

Debate continues about when the Anthropocene formally began. Some scholars anchor it to the Industrial Revolution and the onset of large-scale fossil fuel combustion in the late eighteenth century. Others argue that the most scientifically defensible boundary is the 'Great Acceleration' of the mid-twentieth century, when the combined impacts of population growth, industrialisation, agricultural intensification, and nuclear testing produced changes that are clearly and globally detectable in the stratigraphic record. The latter view was supported by the Anthropocene Working Group, which in 2023 proposed that Crawford Lake in Canada be designated as the reference site for this transition, based on the presence of radioactive fallout markers in its sediments.`,
  question: "What does the passage identify as the most scientifically defensible starting point for the Anthropocene?",
