  id: '117',
  title: 'The Economics of Education',
  text: `Education has long been understood by economists as a form of human capital investment: by acquiring knowledge and skills, individuals increase their productive capacity and, in theory, their lifetime earnings. This framework has been enormously influential in shaping both national education policies and international development priorities. The human capital model justifies public investment in education primarily on economic grounds — educated populations are more productive, pay more taxes, and generate the innovation that drives long-run growth.

Critics of the human capital framework argue that it reduces the inherently multidimensional purposes of education — including the cultivation of critical thinking, democratic citizenship, cultural participation, and personal flourishing — to a single economic metric. The framework is also challenged empirically by the 'education-earnings puzzle': in many countries, rapid increases in educational attainment have not produced proportionate gains in productivity or wages, suggesting that signalling — the use of credentials to communicate pre-existing ability to employers rather than to develop new skills — may play a larger role than human capital models acknowledge.

A significant body of research documents the relationship between education quality and economic outcomes more carefully, finding that it is the quality of learning — measured by cognitive skill acquisition — rather than years of schooling per se that drives economic returns. Countries with high enrolment rates but poor learning outcomes show limited economic benefits from their educational investment, a pattern that has prompted calls for refocusing international development priorities from access to quality.

The distributional dimensions of education economics are also widely studied. Returns to education are not uniform across individuals: those from disadvantaged socioeconomic backgrounds typically face higher barriers to accessing quality education and lower returns on their educational investments, reflecting how education systems can perpetuate as well as challenge social inequality.`,
