  id: '118',
  title: 'Sustainable Fashion',
  text: `The fashion industry ranks among the most environmentally damaging sectors of the global economy, responsible for an estimated 8–10% of global carbon emissions, extensive water consumption, chemical pollution from dyeing and finishing processes, and the generation of enormous quantities of textile waste. Fast fashion business models, which rely on high-volume, low-cost production and rapid turnover of styles, have amplified these impacts by compressing the lifecycle of garments and normalising disposability as a consumer expectation.

In response, a sustainable fashion movement has emerged, encompassing a broad range of initiatives from luxury brands repositioning around artisanal quality and longevity to new business models built on clothing rental, resale, and circular design principles that enable garments to be remade or recycled at end of life. Some brands have adopted materials certifications and supply chain transparency initiatives, allowing consumers to verify the environmental and social credentials of their purchases.

However, sustainability in fashion faces significant definitional and verification challenges. 'Greenwashing' — the practice of making misleading environmental claims in marketing without substantive operational change — is widespread in the industry, with regulatory authorities in several jurisdictions initiating enforcement actions against brands for unsubstantiated sustainability claims. The proliferation of private certification schemes of varying rigour further complicates consumer navigation of the market.

Researchers who have examined the lifecycle impacts of sustainable fashion alternatives note that the benefits vary enormously depending on how frequently items are used. A sustainable garment that is worn many times has dramatically lower per-use environmental impact than a conventional garment worn only a few times, which means that consumer behaviour — specifically buying less and keeping garments longer — is at least as important as the materials and processes used in production. Systemic change, researchers emphasise, requires both industry transformation and a fundamental cultural shift away from fashion as a disposable consumer good.`,
