  id: '119',
  title: 'The Neuroscience of Addiction',
  text: `Addiction is now widely understood by neuroscientists and clinical psychiatrists as a chronic brain disorder rather than a moral failing or a simple matter of insufficient willpower. This reconceptualisation has transformed how addiction is researched, treated, and, in some jurisdictions, how it is addressed through law and social policy. At its neurological core, addiction involves the hijacking of the brain's reward circuitry — the dopaminergic pathways that evolved to motivate behaviours essential to survival such as eating and reproduction — by substances or behaviours that produce artificially intense reward signals.

Repeated exposure to addictive substances produces a cascade of neuroadaptive changes. Tolerance develops as the brain downregulates its dopamine signalling in response to repeated overstimulation, meaning that greater quantities of the substance are needed to produce the same effect. Withdrawal occurs when the substance is removed, as the brain — now recalibrated to expect elevated dopamine stimulation — struggles to function without it. Perhaps most consequential is the sensitisation of brain circuits associated with craving and compulsive seeking: even after prolonged abstinence, exposure to cues associated with prior substance use — a smell, a location, a social context — can trigger powerful cravings through conditioned responses that bypass conscious deliberation.

This neurological understanding has significant clinical implications. Pharmacological treatments that target dopamine or opioid receptor systems can reduce cravings and withdrawal symptoms, improving outcomes in addiction treatment. However, medication alone is rarely sufficient: the social, psychological, and environmental factors that predispose individuals to addiction — including trauma, adverse childhood experiences, poverty, social isolation, and mental illness — must also be addressed for recovery to be sustained. The complexity of addiction has led to growing support for integrated treatment models that combine pharmacotherapy with psychological and social support, and for harm reduction policies that prioritise the health of people who use drugs over punitive enforcement.`,
