  id: '120',
  title: 'Post-Colonial Cities',
  text: `The cities of the Global South bear the structural imprint of their colonial histories in ways that continue to shape inequality, spatial organisation, and economic development in the present. Colonial urban planning was typically designed not to serve the needs of colonised populations but to facilitate the extraction of resources, the administration of territory, and the residential segregation of colonial officials and settlers from indigenous and migrant labour populations. The spatial logics of colonial urbanism — including the concentration of infrastructure and public services in designated European or administrative zones and the relegation of working-class indigenous populations to peripheral, under-serviced areas — proved remarkably durable beyond formal independence.

Post-colonial urban scholars have documented the ways in which these spatial inequalities have been reproduced and sometimes deepened through the policies of post-colonial states, international development institutions, and private real estate markets. The continued concentration of economic opportunity, quality education, healthcare, and public infrastructure in the central urban areas inherited from the colonial period creates self-reinforcing cycles of advantage and disadvantage that are difficult to disrupt through conventional urban policy interventions.

At the same time, it would be misleading to understand post-colonial cities purely as passive inheritors of colonial structures. Residents of marginalised urban areas have consistently demonstrated remarkable capacities for self-organisation, informal economic activity, and community infrastructure development. Practices such as the collective construction of housing, the development of informal credit systems, and the organisation of local markets represent adaptive strategies that both mitigate and highlight the structural inequalities embedded in post-colonial urban environments.`,
