    "title": "Epigenetics and Environment",
    "text": "Epigenetics — the study of heritable changes in gene expression that occur without alterations to the underlying DNA sequence — has fundamentally complicated the classical distinction between nature and nurture in shaping biological outcomes. While the genetic code itself is largely fixed at conception, the epigenome — the layer of chemical modifications that regulate which genes are expressed and at what levels — is dynamic and responsive to environmental signals throughout life.\n\nEpigenetic mechanisms include DNA methylation, in which methyl groups are added to DNA bases in ways that typically silence gene expression, and histone modification, which alters the accessibility of DNA to the transcriptional machinery. These mechanisms allow environmental factors — including nutrition, stress, toxic exposures, physical activity, and social experience — to leave chemical marks on the genome that influence biological function in ways that can persist for years or even decades.\n\nOf particular scientific and social significance is the evidence for transgenerational epigenetic inheritance: the transmission of environmentally acquired epigenetic marks from parents to offspring. Studies in both animals and humans suggest that traumatic experiences, nutritional deficiencies, or toxic exposures experienced by parents can influence the biological profiles of their children and, in some cases, grandchildren, through epigenetic mechanisms. This finding has profound implications for understanding the biological legacy of historical traumas such as famine, war, and systematic discrimination.\n\nEpigenetic research has also generated a new perspective on the developmental origins of health and disease. The first one thousand days of life — from conception to two years of age — are now recognised as a critical window during which environmental conditions have disproportionate and long-lasting influence on the epigenome, shaping susceptibility to chronic diseases including cardiovascular disease, diabetes, and mental illness throughout the life course. This understanding has strengthened the scientific case for early childhood investment as a public health and economic priority.",
