    "id": "122",
    "title": "The Future of Nuclear Energy",
    "text": "Nuclear energy occupies a paradoxical position in contemporary energy policy debates. It produces electricity with very low lifecycle carbon emissions — comparable to wind and solar power on this metric — and delivers reliable baseload power that does not depend on weather conditions. These characteristics make it attractive in the context of decarbonising electricity systems that must remain stable and affordable. Yet the technology remains deeply controversial, shadowed by the catastrophic accidents at Chernobyl and Fukushima, the unresolved challenge of managing high-level radioactive waste, and the association between civilian nuclear programmes and nuclear weapons proliferation.\n\nThe existing fleet of nuclear power stations in many countries is ageing, and the record of new nuclear construction in Western democracies over the past two decades has been poor — plagued by massive cost overruns and construction delays that have made new large-scale nuclear projects economically uncompetitive with rapidly falling renewable energy costs in many markets. The United Kingdom's Hinkley Point C project and the Vogtle plant in the United States are frequently cited as cautionary examples of how complex regulatory requirements, skills attrition in the nuclear construction industry, and supply chain fragmentation can multiply costs far beyond initial projections.\n\nAgainst this backdrop, significant interest has emerged in small modular reactors (SMRs) — compact, factory-built nuclear reactor designs that proponents claim can be constructed more quickly, cheaply, and flexibly than conventional large-scale plants. SMRs have attracted both public and private investment, with several designs in various stages of development and regulatory approval in multiple countries. Critics, however, note that SMRs remain unproven at commercial scale and that their economic competitiveness has yet to be demonstrated in real-world deployment, making the current enthusiasm difficult to assess without empirical evidence from operational projects.",
