    "title": "The Psychology of Groups",
    "text": "Human beings are profoundly social creatures whose cognition, emotion, and behaviour are shaped to a degree that is easy to underestimate by the groups to which they belong and the social identities they hold. Social identity theory, developed by Henri Tajfel and John Turner in the 1970s and 1980s, proposes that a significant component of an individual's self-concept is derived from their membership in social groups — whether defined by nationality, religion, profession, ethnicity, or any other salient category.\n\nA consistent and somewhat sobering finding in social identity research is the tendency toward in-group favouritism and out-group discrimination, even when groups are formed around entirely arbitrary criteria. In Tajfel's original 'minimal group' experiments, participants allocated to groups on the basis of trivial or random criteria — such as aesthetic preferences for abstract paintings — nonetheless favoured members of their own group in resource allocation tasks, even at the cost of maximising their own absolute outcomes. This finding suggests that intergroup bias does not require genuine conflict of interest, competition for scarce resources, or deep ideological disagreement: the mere act of categorisation into groups appears sufficient to activate preferential treatment of in-group members.\n\nThe implications for intergroup conflict, discrimination, and cooperation are extensive. Research has also documented the phenomenon of group polarisation: when like-minded individuals deliberate together, their views tend to shift toward more extreme versions of their initial position. This process is thought to operate through two mechanisms — social comparison (individuals adjust their expressed views to align with or exceed the group norm) and persuasive arguments (within a like-minded group, most arguments encountered reinforce rather than challenge existing beliefs). Both mechanisms contribute to the ideological divergence between groups observed in polarised societies.",
