    "id": "124",
    "title": "Debt and Developing Nations",
    "text": "Sovereign debt crises in developing countries represent one of the most persistent and politically charged challenges in international economics. When governments borrow in foreign currencies to finance development, infrastructure, or consumption needs, they expose themselves to the risk that currency depreciation, rising global interest rates, or adverse economic shocks will make repayment obligations unmanageable. In such circumstances, countries may face a painful choice between servicing external debt — which often requires cutting social expenditures — and investing in the public goods needed for development and social stability.\n\nThe history of sovereign debt crises in the Global South is closely intertwined with the history of international financial institutions. The International Monetary Fund's structural adjustment programmes of the 1980s and 1990s — which conditioned emergency lending on liberalisation, privatisation, and austerity measures — generated lasting controversy, with critics arguing that their social costs fell disproportionately on the poorest members of debtor societies while failing to produce the promised growth dividends. The debt relief initiatives of the late 1990s and 2000s, including the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries initiative, provided some relief but did not fundamentally resolve the structural vulnerabilities that make low-income countries repeatedly susceptible to debt crises.\n\nContemporary debt challenges in developing countries have been compounded by the growing role of bilateral creditors — particularly China, which has become a major lender to low-income countries through its Belt and Road Initiative — and private bondholders, neither of whom are automatically bound by the multilateral debt relief frameworks designed for an earlier era of predominantly Western government and multilateral lending. The opacity of some bilateral lending agreements and concerns about debt sustainability have renewed debates about the need for a more comprehensive and equitable international sovereign debt resolution mechanism.",
