    "id": "125",
    "title": "Language and Thought",
    "text": "The relationship between language and thought is one of the oldest and most enduring questions in cognitive science and philosophy of mind. The strong version of the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis — known as linguistic determinism — proposes that language not only influences but wholly determines the structure of thought: that it is impossible to conceive of ideas for which one's language has no words or grammatical categories. In its strong form, this thesis is now largely rejected by mainstream cognitive science, which has accumulated substantial evidence that conceptual thought can occur independently of linguistic expression.\n\nHowever, a weaker version of the hypothesis — linguistic relativity — has attracted renewed empirical support. Research has demonstrated that the specific structures and categories of a language can influence non-linguistic cognitive tasks in measurable ways. For example, languages that mark grammatical gender assign masculine or feminine gender to inanimate objects, and studies suggest that speakers of these languages associate psychological attributes with objects that match the gender assigned in their language — German speakers may associate 'bridge' (die Brücke, feminine) with gentleness, while Spanish speakers associate 'bridge' (el puente, masculine) with strength. Similarly, languages with rich systems for encoding spatial relations, such as Guugu Yimithirr (an Australian Aboriginal language that uses cardinal directions rather than egocentric terms like 'left' and 'right'), have been linked to extraordinary spatial navigation abilities in their speakers.\n\nResearch on colour perception has provided some of the most rigorous tests of linguistic relativity. Languages carve up the colour spectrum differently, and cross-cultural studies have shown that colour discrimination at the boundary of named colour categories is faster in the right visual field (processed by the language-dominant left hemisphere) than in the left, suggesting that linguistic colour categories directly affect perceptual processing rather than merely post-hoc labelling.",
