    "id": "126",
    "title": "The Economics of Healthcare",
    "text": "Healthcare markets possess a set of structural features that make them behave very differently from the idealised competitive markets described in introductory economics textbooks. In standard competitive markets, informed consumers choose among competing suppliers based on price and quality, driving efficiency through market discipline. Healthcare markets deviate from this model in multiple systematic ways that justify, in the view of most health economists, substantial public intervention in their organisation and financing.\n\nThe most fundamental deviation is the problem of information asymmetry: patients generally lack the medical expertise to evaluate the necessity or quality of the treatments they are recommended, creating a situation in which providers can recommend more services than are medically justified — a problem economists call supplier-induced demand. A related problem is the third-party payment structure that characterises most advanced healthcare systems: because patients in insurance-based systems do not bear the full cost of individual healthcare decisions at the point of use, they have limited incentive to consider cost when seeking or consenting to treatment, potentially driving overconsumption.\n\nHealthcare also exhibits characteristics of a 'credence good' — a category of product whose quality cannot be assessed even after consumption. A patient who recovers after a medical procedure cannot reliably determine whether the recovery was caused by the treatment or would have occurred regardless. This makes quality competition among healthcare providers difficult to sustain in the way that quality competition functions in markets for experience goods.\n\nThe interaction between these market failures and the strong social norm in most societies that access to healthcare should not depend primarily on ability to pay has produced a wide variety of national healthcare financing systems — from the single-payer universal systems characteristic of Canada and Scandinavia to the more pluralistic insurance-based systems of Germany and Switzerland and the predominantly private system of the United States — each representing a different approach to balancing efficiency, equity, and individual choice.",
