    "id": "127",
    "title": "Dark Matter and Dark Energy",
    "text": "Contemporary cosmology confronts a profound empirical puzzle: the matter and energy described by the Standard Model of particle physics — all the atoms, molecules, and radiation that make up everything directly observable in the universe — accounts for only approximately 5% of the universe's total energy content. The remaining 95% consists of two poorly understood components: dark matter (approximately 27%) and dark energy (approximately 68%), whose existence is inferred from their gravitational and cosmological effects rather than from direct detection.\n\nDark matter was first postulated to explain the 'galaxy rotation problem'. Observations of spiral galaxies show that stars at the outer edges rotate around the galactic centre at speeds that, according to Newtonian gravity, should only be possible if there is far more mass in and around galaxies than is visible. The distribution of this inferred invisible mass — forming extended 'halos' around visible galaxies — explains observed galactic dynamics and the large-scale structure of the universe as revealed by galaxy surveys and the cosmic microwave background. Multiple independent lines of evidence now converge on the existence of dark matter, but its particle nature remains unknown. Numerous candidate particles — including weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs) and axions — have been proposed, but despite decades of experimental searches, none has been definitively detected.\n\nDark energy is even more mysterious. Discovered through observations of distant supernovae in 1998 — which revealed that the expansion of the universe is accelerating rather than decelerating as gravity should cause — dark energy represents an energy density apparently inherent to empty space itself. The leading theoretical candidate, the cosmological constant, is consistent with observations but cannot currently be explained from first principles: quantum field theory predicts a vacuum energy density roughly 120 orders of magnitude larger than what is observed, a discrepancy sometimes described as the worst prediction in the history of physics.",
