    "id": "129",
    "title": "The Architecture of Inequality",
    "text": "Urban space is not politically neutral. The physical design of cities — the placement of roads, public transport routes, parks, schools, healthcare facilities, and housing — reflects and reproduces social hierarchies, embedding the priorities of those with the power to shape the built environment into the landscape for generations. Critical urban scholars argue that many seemingly technical decisions in urban planning — about zoning, infrastructure investment, and spatial connectivity — function as mechanisms of social exclusion that determine which communities have access to opportunity and which are systematically marginalised.\n\nThe history of urban planning in the United States provides extensive documentation of these dynamics. The practice of 'redlining' — the denial of mortgage and insurance services to residents of predominantly Black neighbourhoods, mapped and enforced by the Federal Housing Administration — physically concentrated poverty and disinvestment in specific urban areas whose effects persist in spatial patterns of wealth and health inequality visible today. Highway construction projects of the mid-twentieth century systematically demolished or bisected established Black and working-class neighbourhoods, severing social networks and displacing communities while connecting predominantly white suburban populations to city centres.\n\nContemporary manifestations of spatial inequality include the unequal provision of greenspace, the concentration of environmental hazards such as waste processing facilities and industrial pollution in low-income and minority neighbourhoods, and the siting of high-quality schools in areas accessible only to those who can afford nearby housing. The concept of 'spatial justice' — developed by scholars including Henri Lefebvre and Edward Soja — argues that the right to the city encompasses not only access to urban resources but the right to participate meaningfully in shaping the spaces one inhabits. Achieving spatial justice requires both the redistribution of urban resources and the democratisation of planning processes.",
