    "title": "The Science of Climate Tipping Points",
    "text": "Climate tipping points are thresholds in the Earth system at which relatively small additional changes in temperature or other climate variables trigger self-reinforcing feedback processes that can push major components of the climate system into qualitatively different states — often irreversibly, on human timescales. Unlike the gradual, roughly proportional responses that characterise most climate variables, tipping point dynamics involve non-linearity: the system may appear stable for extended periods and then shift rapidly and dramatically once a critical threshold is crossed.\n\nAmong the tipping elements that scientists consider most concerning are the West Antarctic and Greenland ice sheets, whose destabilisation would contribute multi-metre sea level rise over centuries; the Amazon rainforest, which could transition from rainforest to a drier savannah state if deforestation and warming cross a critical threshold, releasing enormous quantities of stored carbon; Arctic permafrost, which stores approximately twice as much carbon as is currently in the atmosphere and which is already thawing at accelerating rates, releasing methane and CO₂; and the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC), the ocean current system that moderates the climate of Western Europe and whose weakening could have profound effects on regional climate patterns across the Northern Hemisphere.\n\nA 2022 analysis published in Science identified sixteen tipping elements for which current evidence suggests that critical thresholds may be crossed at global warming levels between 1.5°C and 2°C above pre-industrial temperatures — levels that are within reach under current emissions trajectories. Of particular concern is the possibility of 'tipping cascades' — the triggering of one tipping point could increase the likelihood of others, creating compound risks that are far more dangerous than any single tipping element in isolation. This finding has strengthened scientific arguments for urgent and dramatic emissions reductions, as the consequences of overshooting moderate warming targets may be both severe and effectively irreversible.",
