    "id": "132",
    "title": "Media Framing and Public Opinion",
    "text": "Framing theory in communication research examines how the presentation of information — the selection of particular aspects of a topic, the choice of language, the use of visual imagery, and the narrative structures through which events are contextualised — shapes how audiences understand, evaluate, and respond to that information, often independently of the factual content itself. Framing is not a marginal phenomenon: it is inherent to all acts of communication, since no message can present all potentially relevant information simultaneously, and every selection involves a perspective.\n\nExperimental research has consistently demonstrated that different frames for identical information produce measurably different attitudes, risk perceptions, and policy preferences. In a classic experiment by Amos Tversky and Daniel Kahneman, respondents were presented with a public health scenario in which an intervention was described either as saving 200 out of 600 lives (a gain frame) or as resulting in 400 deaths out of 600 (a loss frame) — the outcomes are mathematically identical, but the loss frame produced significantly greater risk aversion. This finding extended the concept of loss aversion from individual economic decisions to public policy reasoning.\n\nIn the context of news media, framing research has examined how issues as diverse as climate change, immigration, crime, and poverty are presented in ways that systematically favour certain interpretations and policy responses over others. Episodic framing — presenting social issues through the lens of individual stories and cases — tends to produce attributions of responsibility to individuals, while thematic framing — contextualising issues within broader social and structural contexts — tends to produce attributions of systemic responsibility. Research suggests that episodic framing is strongly prevalent in commercial news media, which may contribute to public underestimation of structural factors in social problems and an overemphasis on individual-level explanations and solutions.",
