    "id": "133",
    "title": "The Paradox of Choice",
    "text": "Contemporary consumer societies celebrate choice as an unambiguous good — a reflection of individual freedom and the responsive efficiency of market systems. The expansion of choice, in this view, is straightforwardly welfare-enhancing: more options allow each individual to find the product, service, or experience that most precisely matches their unique preferences. Psychologist Barry Schwartz challenged this assumption in his influential work 'The Paradox of Choice', arguing that beyond a certain threshold, an increase in the number of available options can reduce rather than enhance wellbeing, generating decision paralysis, post-decision regret, and opportunity cost anxiety.\n\nThe psychological mechanisms underlying the paradox are well documented. When faced with an overwhelming array of options, individuals often experience decision paralysis — an inability to choose at all, despite the presence of options that would objectively improve their situation. Research by Sheena Iyengar and Mark Lepper found that consumers presented with a sample of six jams were significantly more likely to make a purchase than those presented with twenty-four jams, despite the larger assortment being rated as more attractive.\n\nEven after making a choice, individuals in high-choice environments are more susceptible to regret and counterfactual thinking — the tendency to imagine how a different choice might have turned out. This 'maximiser' orientation — the pursuit of the objectively best option rather than a satisfactory one — is associated with higher decision-making effort, greater post-decision regret, and, paradoxically, lower overall life satisfaction than the 'satisficer' approach of selecting the first option that meets a predetermined threshold of acceptability.\n\nThe paradox of choice has influenced product design, policy, and retirement plan architecture, with 'choice architects' increasingly focusing on reducing complexity and establishing well-designed defaults rather than maximising option variety.",
