    "text": "Earth's orbital environment is facing a growing crisis of congestion and contamination. Since the launch of Sputnik in 1957, more than 10,000 satellites have been placed in orbit, and the pace of launches has accelerated dramatically with the entry of commercial operators and the deployment of large constellations of small satellites for broadband internet provision. The United States Space Surveillance Network currently tracks over 27,000 pieces of debris larger than 10 centimetres in low Earth orbit, but estimates of the total debris population — including fragments too small to track — run into the hundreds of millions.\n\nEven very small debris fragments pose serious risks to operational satellites and crewed spacecraft: at orbital velocities of several kilometres per second, a one-centimetre fragment carries kinetic energy comparable to a hand grenade. The International Space Station regularly performs evasive manoeuvres to avoid tracked debris, and several operational satellites have been destroyed by debris impacts. The Kessler Syndrome — first theorised by NASA scientist Donald Kessler in 1978 — describes a potential cascade scenario in which collisions between debris objects generate additional fragments, increasing collision probabilities and ultimately rendering certain orbital altitudes unusable for decades or centuries.\n\nInternational governance of the orbital environment remains fragmented and inadequate. Existing guidelines for debris mitigation — such as the 25-year deorbit rule for satellites in low Earth orbit — are voluntary and unevenly observed. The emergence of so-called 'megaconstellations' — satellite networks numbering in the thousands or tens of thousands — has made the adequacy of existing frameworks urgent, as the sheer number of objects creates collision risks and produces light pollution that concerns astronomers. Active debris removal technologies are under development, but no international framework currently assigns liability or responsibility for debris remediation.",
