    "id": "137",
    "title": "The Limits of Empathy",
    "text": "Empathy — the imaginative projection of oneself into the subjective experience of another — occupies an almost unassailable position in contemporary moral discourse, widely regarded as the emotional foundation of ethical behaviour and compassionate social policy. Its elevation to moral primacy reflects a powerful intuition: that if we could truly feel what others feel, the barriers to altruism, justice, and solidarity would dissolve. Yet a growing body of philosophical and empirical work suggests that this veneration of empathy may rest on serious conceptual and practical misunderstandings about how moral motivation actually operates.\n\nPaul Bloom, in his influential critique 'Against Empathy', argues that empathy is structurally ill-suited to serve as a reliable guide to moral action precisely because of its most celebrated quality: its vividness and immediacy. Because empathy is a spotlight rather than a floodlight, it illuminates individual suffering with intense clarity while leaving statistically larger but less visually available suffering in comparative darkness. The result is a systematic distortion of moral attention: a single identifiable victim reliably commands more concern and resources than thousands of statistical lives, a phenomenon documented across charitable giving, policy responses, and judicial decisions.\n\nA second structural limitation is empathy's susceptibility to in-group bias. People empathise far more readily with those who are similar to them — in ethnicity, nationality, class, or social world — creating a mechanism that can entrench rather than dissolve social division. Far from being a universal solvent for prejudice, empathy activated along in-group lines can intensify hostility toward perceived out-groups by heightening the emotional salience of threats to those with whom we empathise.\n\nBloom and others propose that impartial concern — a more deliberative orientation toward the welfare of others that does not depend on vivid emotional simulation — may be a more reliable and equitable guide to ethical action than empathy, however emotionally satisfying the latter may be.",
