    "id": "138",
    "title": "Postmodernism and Truth",
    "text": "The relationship between postmodernism and truth is among the most contested and frequently caricatured topics in contemporary intellectual life. Critics — particularly those from analytic philosophy and the natural sciences — have charged that postmodern theory, by treating knowledge as a social construction and interrogating the power relations embedded in claims to objectivity, effectively dissolves the distinction between well-evidenced and poorly evidenced claims, enabling the convenient relativism that underwrites climate denial, conspiracy theory, and political authoritarianism. This charge is not without rhetorical force, and the spectacle of politicians appropriating the language of epistemic uncertainty to discredit inconvenient expertise lends it surface plausibility.\n\nWhat this critique typically misunderstands, however, is the distinction between postmodernism's rejection of foundationalism — the view that knowledge requires an absolute, culture-independent bedrock of certainty — and a wholesale rejection of the possibility of better and worse claims about the world. The more sophisticated strands of postmodern epistemology, associated with thinkers such as Richard Rorty and Donna Haraway, do not deny that some accounts of reality are more empirically adequate, more internally coherent, or more practically useful than others. What they reject is the claim that any such account can be secured by appeal to a viewpoint-independent, 'God's-eye' perspective that transcends all social situatedness.\n\nHaraway's concept of 'situated knowledge' exemplifies this position: the acknowledgment that all knowledge is produced from a particular vantage point, by particular kinds of knowers, in particular historical circumstances, does not lead to the conclusion that all knowledge claims are equally valid. On the contrary, it demands rigorous attention to the positionality of knowledge producers and the ways in which social location shapes what can be known, by whom, and under what conditions — a demand that is arguably more epistemically demanding, not less, than the naive objectivism it critiques.",
