    "id": "139",
    "title": "The Political Economy of Automation",
    "text": "The fear that labour-replacing technology will produce mass structural unemployment — a concern that has surfaced at each major technological transition from the mechanisation of agriculture to the diffusion of computing — has never, in the historical record, been definitively vindicated. The standard economic response, known as the 'lump of labour fallacy' rebuttal, holds that technological displacement is offset by productivity gains that lower prices, expand markets, and create demand for new categories of work that cannot be anticipated in advance. History, proponents argue, has consistently validated this view: despite two centuries of dramatic labour-saving technological change, employment participation rates in developed economies have remained broadly stable.\n\nHowever, there are reasons to believe that automation driven by artificial intelligence may be categorically different from earlier technological transitions in ways that weaken the historical analogy. Previous automation primarily substituted for routine physical and, subsequently, routine cognitive tasks, leaving non-routine cognitive and interpersonal tasks relatively unaffected. Current AI systems are demonstrating capacity in precisely these domains — legal reasoning, creative production, diagnosis, complex analysis — that were previously considered definitively beyond automation's reach. If the non-routine cognitive tasks that historically provided refuge for workers displaced from earlier automation are themselves subject to substitution, the standard rebound mechanism may be substantially disrupted.\n\nThe distributional consequences are as important as the aggregate employment effects, and arguably more politically consequential. Even if total employment remains stable, automation may systematically hollow out middle-skill occupations — creating a bifurcated labour market in which high-skill, high-wage workers in non-automatable roles coexist with a growing mass of low-skill, low-wage service workers — with profound implications for wage inequality, social mobility, and the political economy of democratic governance. The question that contemporary labour economists most urgently face is not whether automation destroys jobs in aggregate, but how it redistributes the gains and losses.",
