    "title": "The Concept of Sovereignty",
    "text": "Sovereignty — the supreme authority of a political entity over a defined territory and population, immune from external interference in its domestic affairs — has served as the foundational organising concept of the international order since the Peace of Westphalia of 1648. Yet the concept has always been less theoretically coherent than its institutional centrality suggests, and the pressures of globalisation, human rights norms, transnational governance, and the recent reassertion of great power competition have exposed its internal tensions with renewed force.\n\nThe classical Westphalian conception of sovereignty is normatively thin: it establishes formal legal equality between states and the principle of non-interference without making any demands about the internal character of the sovereign regime. This formal equality sits in permanent tension with the substantive inequalities of power that actually structure international relations, creating a system that functions largely to protect the legal prerogatives of established states while providing limited recourse for populations subjected to atrocious governance.\n\nThe emergence of the human rights framework after 1945 introduced a competing normative logic that has never been fully reconciled with Westphalian sovereignty. The Responsibility to Protect doctrine, adopted by the United Nations in 2005, attempted to resolve this tension by reconceptualising sovereignty not as an unconditional right but as a conditional responsibility: states earn sovereign protection by fulfilling their protective obligations toward their populations, and forfeit that protection when they engage in atrocity crimes. In practice, the doctrine has been applied selectively, controversially, and inconsistently, reflecting the deep resistance of states — particularly great powers with their own territorial and normative interests — to accepting principles that could be invoked against them. The central unresolved question is whether international norms can genuinely constrain sovereign behaviour or whether they remain, in final analysis, instruments of the powerful.",
