    "title": "Consciousness and the Hard Problem",
    "text": "The 'hard problem of consciousness' — a phrase coined by philosopher David Chalmers in 1995 — designates the explanatory gap between the objective, third-person description of neural processes and the subjective, first-person character of conscious experience. The 'easy problems' of consciousness — explaining how the brain discriminates stimuli, integrates information, reports mental states, and controls behaviour — are described as 'easy' not because they are simple but because they are in principle tractable by the standard methods of cognitive neuroscience and computational modelling: they require only the explanation of functional mechanisms. The hard problem, by contrast, asks why any physical process — however complex and highly organised — should be accompanied by subjective experience at all: why there is 'something it is like' to see red or feel pain rather than these processes occurring 'in the dark'.\n\nPhysicalist responses to the hard problem broadly take two forms. Eliminativist physicalism denies that the hard problem correctly identifies a genuine explanatory target: subjective experience as ordinarily conceived simply does not exist as a distinct phenomenon to be explained, and a mature neuroscience will dissolve rather than solve the problem. Reductive physicalism maintains that subjective experience does exist but will ultimately prove explicable in entirely physical terms, once our understanding of neural mechanisms is sufficiently advanced — a view Chalmers has challenged by arguing that such explanations always leave the explanatory gap intact, even in thought-experiment scenarios of physically perfect brain replicas (philosophical zombies) that behave like conscious beings but putatively lack inner experience.\n\nNon-physicalist approaches, including property dualism and panpsychism, accept that the hard problem resists purely physical explanation and argue that consciousness requires either irreducibly mental properties or that experience is a fundamental feature of physical reality at a more basic level than macroscopic neural organisation. Both approaches carry significant metaphysical costs that their proponents must either accept or seek to minimise.",
