    "title": "Financialisation and the Real Economy",
    "text": "Financialisation — the process by which financial motives, financial markets, financial actors, and financial institutions have come to play an increasingly dominant role in the operation of domestic and international economies — is among the most consequential structural transformations of the late twentieth and early twenty-first centuries. The term encompasses a range of interrelated phenomena: the growth of the financial sector relative to productive industry, the increasing orientation of non-financial corporations toward shareholder value maximisation over investment and employment, the expansion of household debt and asset ownership as mechanisms of welfare provision, and the deepening integration of global financial markets that has enabled capital to move across borders in response to marginal differences in return.\n\nGerald Epstein's canonical definition characterises financialisation as 'the increasing role of financial motives, financial markets, financial actors, and financial institutions in the operation of domestic and foreign economies.' What this formulation captures is the degree to which finance has moved from being a facilitator of productive economic activity — channelling savings toward investment in goods and services — to being a domain of value extraction in its own right, in which returns are generated through financial engineering, arbitrage, and rent extraction rather than through the creation of productive capacity.\n\nCritics argue that financialisation has profoundly altered corporate behaviour through the dominance of the 'shareholder value' ideology, which since the 1980s has incentivised corporate managers to prioritise share price and dividend payments over long-term investment, research and development, and employee compensation. The empirical consequences are documented in the secular decline of corporate investment rates in productive capital in many advanced economies, the shortening of corporate planning horizons, and the growth of share buybacks as the dominant mode of deploying corporate cash flows. These trends carry macroeconomic consequences — dampening productivity growth, suppressing wage growth, and amplifying business cycle volatility — that extend far beyond the corporate sector.",
