    "id": "149",
    "title": "The Philosophy of Time",
    "text": "Few problems in philosophy resist resolution as tenaciously as the nature of time. Augustine of Hippo articulated the paradox with characteristic elegance in his Confessions: 'What then is time? If no one asks me, I know; if I wish to explain it to one who asks, I know not.' Contemporary philosophy of time remains fractured along lines that have proven surprisingly resistant to empirical adjudication, partly because the questions at stake concern not what our best physical theories say about time but what those theories mean — an interpretive enterprise that physics alone cannot settle.\n\nThe central metaphysical dispute concerns the ontological status of the past, present, and future. Presentism holds that only the present moment exists; past events have ceased to be and future events have not yet come to be. The growing block universe view holds that both the past and the present exist, with the universe understood as a block of spacetime that is continuously growing as the future becomes the present and the present becomes past. Eternalism — sometimes called the block universe or four-dimensionalism — holds that all moments of time exist with equal ontological status, with 'now' designating a perspective-relative indexical rather than an objectively privileged moment in the structure of reality.\n\nThe special theory of relativity poses a significant problem for presentism and growing block theories, as the relativity of simultaneity implies that there is no observer-independent fact about which events are happening 'now' — the set of events that constitute the present depends on the reference frame of the observer. Eternalism accommodates this naturally, since it does not require a privileged present. However, eternalism faces its own difficulties: it struggles to account for the phenomenological asymmetry between past and future — the directionality of causation, the openness of the future to choice, the irreversibility of the past — treating these as perspectival illusions rather than fundamental features of reality.",
