    "id": "150",
    "title": "The Anthropology of Capitalism",
    "text": "Anthropological approaches to capitalism distinguish themselves from economic and sociological accounts by their insistence on treating capitalism not as a universal logic that manifests identically across contexts but as a set of practices, values, and social relations that is always embedded in and transformed by the particular cultural, historical, and ecological contexts in which it operates. This commitment to attending to difference and particularity does not imply that capitalism lacks systematic features or that it is reducible to an aggregate of purely local phenomena; rather, it resists the methodological universalism that has historically treated European or North American capitalist forms as the unmarked standard against which all other capitalisms are measured as deviations or inadequacies.\n\nAnna Tsing's notion of 'friction' — developed through her ethnography of global capitalism in the Indonesian rainforest — captures something important here: global capitalism does not roll out uniformly across the surface of the world but produces its characteristic patterns of accumulation and dispossession through the particular resistances, collaborations, misunderstandings, and accommodations it encounters in specific places and with specific people. The universalising aspirations of capital are always mediated by the irreducible specificity of the encounters through which they are actualised.\n\nThis perspective has important analytical consequences. It reveals that the apparent uniformity of global capitalism is itself an achievement — something produced and maintained through constant work, negotiation, and the suppression of alternatives — rather than a natural or inevitable outcome. It also foregrounds the agency of communities and individuals who are not merely subjects of capitalist processes but active, if differentially positioned, participants in their local elaboration. At the same time, it demands vigilance against the romantic overestimation of local resistance and the underestimation of the structural asymmetries of power that shape what kinds of accommodation and resistance are actually available in any given context.",
